{
  "doc_id": "59285",
  "text": "Experimental studies suggest that RA plays a critical role in regulating cardiac structure and function throughout life [CITATION_1] . During early stages of cardiogenesis, RA excess produces congenital defects related to abnormal folding and septation of the outflow tract and cardiac chambers [CITATION_2] . Likewise, excess of RA signaling (overexpression of RA receptor or retinoid X receptor) results in cardiomyocyte abnormalities and dilated cardiomyopathy [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] . In contrast, vitamin A-deficient animals and receptor knockout models have thin myocardial walls, and the embryos develop a generalized edema associated with heart failure [CITATION_6] .",
